        <mxCell id="qpx9_JxaJNKu9rihZONX-141" value="(b) Your friendly TA Tony challenges you to quickly implement an integer maxheap data structure. However, you already have your MinHeap and you don’t&lt;br&gt;feel like writing a whole second data structure. Can you use your min-heap&lt;br&gt;to mimic the behavior of a max-heap? Specifically, we want to be able to get&lt;br&gt;the largest item in the heap in constant time, and add things to the heap in&lt;br&gt;Θ(log n) time, as a normal max heap should.&lt;br&gt;Hint: Although you cannot alter them, you can still use methods from MinHeap.&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Answer: negative when insert and remove&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;" vertex="1" parent="1">
          <mxGeometry x="575" y="20" width="560" height="190" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
